/-

# MATH0109 Assessment guidelines for students

Each assessed sheet and in-class test in this module will consist of a
single Lean file containing `sorrys`.

To complete the assessment you should replace each `sorry` with Lean code
that closes the goal.

Both assessed coursework and in-class tests should be done on your own laptop
and submitted via Moodle.

You will have access to on-line resources (via your laptop) for both
assessed sheets and in-class tests.

Standard UCL plagiarism rules apply, in particular the work you submit should be
your own.


Your work will be assessed primarily in terms of correctness: i.e. does your code
close the goal and are there any errors in your file?

We will deduct marks for code that contains obvious elements of bad style.

The points of style we are most concerned about are issues that would result
in code that is difficult to read or maintain.

For example:

1. Confusing choices of variable names.
2. Indentation that does not demonstrate clearly where multiple goals start/end.
3. Proofs that contain a substantial amount of unnecessary extra code.
 e.g. proofs by induction that do not use the inductive hypothesis.



-/
